<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Class changed In Don't Bank on Us (ITV, 8.30) the World in Action team
promises to set the vital juices flowing by reporting on the unpopularity of
Britain's banks, which have experienced a decline in public esteem surpassed
only by the monarchy. Evidence will be provided to show that the banks are
consistently overcharging to take them through the recession.
Still talking money, but in this case won through straightforward
dishonesty, Cutting Edge: Fraud Squad (C4, 9.0) goes on the trail with the
Metropolitan Fraud Squad and follows successful investigations into three
uncomplicated, small-beer cases.
One of them involves a fraudulent hospital appeal, another is a 'Nigerian
fraud' of the type which, although highly publicised in the last few years,
still manages, remarkably enough, to find gullible victims.
On a markedly more elevated plane, we come a little closer to the Russian
soul with the second part of Writing on the Edge (C4, 11.00), a
semi-dramatised portrayal of the relationship between art and political
commitment in the life of the poet Alexander Pushkin.
