<DATE>930118
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 93 / EC setback for ministers on contracting-out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EUROPEAN Community laws protecting the jobs and pay of workers affected by
company mergers will apply even when public services are contracted out to
the private sector, in the view of UK lawyers assessing the implications of
a recent judgment in the European Court of Justice.
The legal opinion, which is directly contrary to the views of British
ministers, has emerged on the eve of a conference in London organised by the
government about ways in which companies can compete for public services
worth Pounds 1.5bn. Uncertainty about the reach of the Transfer of
Undertakings (Protection of Employment) regulations, known as Tupe, has cast
a shadow over the current extension of contracting-out in central government
services.
The UK government has argued that the Tupe legislation does not normally
apply to contracting out. Private-sector companies taking on work from the
public sector are thus free to sack workers who transfer to them under the
contracts, and alter their pay and conditions.
Mr Michael Forsyth, the employment minister, said last month about
contracting-out: 'There is not normally a transfer of an undertaking in
these circumstances.'
The European court ruled recently in the case of Rask v ISS Kantineservice
that the EC Acquired Rights Directive, on which Tupe is based, does apply
when a service is contracted out.
An analysis of the case by Ms Melanie Tether, a solicitor with the law firm
Norton Rose, says: 'The ruling reflects the willingness of the ECJ to put
the protection of employees' rights before the promotion of commercial
interests.'
The Rask case, which began in Denmark, arose when Philips contracted out its
staff canteen, underlining the fact that Tupe also applies to contracting
out within the private sector. The contractor, ISS, agreed to manage the
canteen in return for a fixed fee. However, Philips continued to own the
premises and equipment. It also retained economic control over the service
provided because it continued to fix the prices charged for food and
restricted the canteen's customers to its own employees.
Ms Tether believes the court has thus backed a minimalist definition of what
does not constitutes a 'transfer' and an 'undertaking' and has undermined
many of the UK government's arguments on the limits of Tupe.
One argument apparently undermined by Rask is that Tupe cannot apply when a
public authority contracts out a service because the statutory duty to
provide that service remains with the relevant authority. The government
argument that no transfer has taken place unless the contractor acquires the
assets used in the service is also disputed by the Rask judgment.
The judgment is likely to alert unions to the fact that Tupe applies to
private sector contracting-out and might even affect routine corporate
restructuring. Private sector contracting-out is a much bigger market than
that in the public sector.
It is not yet clear, however, how long after a transfer the Tupe regulations
will apply.
Editorial Comment, Page 11
</TEXT>
