<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 93 / Mergers and acquisitions surge forecast
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE IS a possibility of a 'mini-boom' in merger and acquisition activity
in the UK this year, Ernst &amp; Young Corporate Finance says today.
It says in its monthly review that, after 'probably the most dismal year
ever' for corporate financiers, the level of company acquisitions should
increase in the coming year.
The review acknowledges that economic uncertainty has left companies
reluctant to embark on corporate acquisitions, an activity which always
involves considerable risks.
But it says that 'as and when there are real, sustained signs of an
improvement in the economy', many of the medium-sized and larger, cash-rich
public companies will decide the time is right to buy.
Mr Richard Mead, national director of corporate finance for Ernst &amp; Young,
says: 'The aftermath of Black Wednesday means that British companies may now
provide good value for money to foreign buyers. When combined with the
larger UK-based companies that have been sitting on cash during the
recession, they provide a pool of potential buyers.'
Ernst &amp; Young also says it expects the upturn in buying interest to coincide
with the emergence of more companies for sale. It envisages that companies
financed in the mid to late 1980s by venture and development capitalists -
often as management buy-outs - will come on the market as backers seek to
realise their investments.
Companies that remain financially stretched but which are going concerns are
also likely to look for new owners, the report concludes.
Ernst &amp; Young stresses that although the outlook suggests an increase in
merger and acquisition activity it will be some time before a sellers'
market reappears.
The review says the expected improvement in the market for selling unquoted
companies 'will be more apparent in the form of an increase in the number of
deals and better saleability than in the form of higher prices'.
The price gap between unquoted and quoted businesses, it adds, is unlikely
to be narrowed substantially.
</TEXT>
