<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 93 / School inspection plans condemned
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A STRONG attack on the government's plans for regular school inspections, a
central feature of Mr John Major's Citizen's Charter, is made in a paper
published today by the Centre for Policy Studies, the rightwing think tank.
Dr Sheila Lawlor, the centre's deputy director, condemns the school
inspection regime being established by the new Office for Standards in
Education (Ofsted) as too prescriptive.
She says it is biased in favour of 'progressive' teaching methods and their
protagonists.
Every state school is to be inspected at least once every four years under
reforms carried through last year by Mr Kenneth Clarke, then education
secretary. Private teams will carry out inspections but will be licensed by
Ofsted, which will also be responsible for assigning inspectors to schools.
Dr Lawlor condemns Ofsted's inspection guidelines as 'too detailed and
prescriptive', requiring over-lengthy inspections - 33 days for secondary
schools with fewer than 400 pupils, 57 days for those with more - covering
too wide a field.
'Unless the basis on which inspection rests is radically different to that
proposed, there is every danger that the new arrangements will perpetuate
the worst of the old system and undermine the central task of the objective
reporting of standards,' argues Dr Lawlor.
She also criticises Ofsted's recruitment and training arrangements as likely
to lead to an inspectorate dominated by the personnel and outlook of Her
Majesty's Inspectorate, the national inspection body prior to Ofsted.
'The upshot will be to perpetuate the poor practices of HMI and local
authorities in the past, in which emphasis is put on schools perpetuating
favoured educational theories rather than on achieving the highest standards
by whatever methods they choose,' she says.
A General Teaching Council should be established in England and Wales 'to
raise the morale of teachers and restore their standing more generally in
society', according to a paper published today by the National Commission on
Education, an independent think tank.
The paper, by Mr Stuart Maclure, former editor of the Times Educational
Supplement, says the powers of the council should include establishing a
register of teachers and administering disciplinary procedures.
Inspecting The School Inspectors, Centre for Policy Studies, 52 Rochester
Row, London SW1P 1JU, Pounds 4.95.
