<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 93 / Supermarket floorspace grows rapidly
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SUPERMARKETS are building outlets more quickly than the grocery market is
expanding, but this is unlikely to produce an all-out price war, says a
survey published today by Verdict, the retailing research company.
Grocers and supermarkets have seen cumulative volume sales growth of 1.1 per
cent over the past three years, the report says, but floorspace has
increased by 7.8 per cent in the same period.
Verdict blames weak sales growth on the recession and the increasing
maturity of the market. It says that with 800 superstores in the UK, and the
big retailers opening about 80 new stores a year, the opportunity to find
new sites with little competition is diminishing.
These factors may explain why the biggest food retailers have resorted to
more aggressive price promotions. Verdict says the price skirmishing is
unlikely to escalate into a war. The big three retailers, J. Sainsbury,
Tesco and Argyll, owner of Safeway, are investing too much in new stores to
be able to cope with the repercussions of heavy discounting.
Verdict on Grocers and Supermarkets 1993, Verdict Research, 112 High
Holborn, London WC1V 6JS. Pounds 695.
Isosceles changes, Page 14
