<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 93 / Gloom abates in finance sector
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MOST FINANCIAL services firms are experiencing lower than normal business
volumes and are no more optimistic about their prospects than they were
three months ago, according to the latest quarterly survey of industry
trends.
The survey, conducted by the Confederation of British Industry and
accountants Coopers and Lybrand, found, however, that 25 per cent of the 309
institutions surveyed in December were more optimistic about business
prospects, up from 3 per cent in the previous quarterly survey conducted in
September.
The only sector of the financial services industry reporting a decline in
optimism was life insurance, where more than half of those surveyed expect
growth to be constrained by the prospect of new legislation.
Overall, 41 per cent of respondents reported a rise in non-performing loans
in the previous three months and 28 per cent said they expected a further
rise in the next three months.
Financial Services Survey Number 13, December 1992. Coopers and Lybrand,
Plumtree Court, London EC4A 4HT. CBI Members Pounds 32, non-CBI members
Pounds 53.
