<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 93 / Consumer optimism 'very low'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONSUMER OPTIMISM about the economy was at a lower level in the last quarter
of last year than at any time since the start two years earlier of a
quarterly survey published jointly by Business Strategies, an economics
consultancy, and Gallup, a market research group.
There were particular concerns late last year about rising unemployment and
inflation according to the survey, which is published today. Northern
regions showed a big slip in consumer confidence.
The survey coincided with Britain's withdrawal last September from the
European exchange rate mechanism, which was a big setback for the
government's economic policy.
Even though the report suggests that confidence in December showed a rise
from the extremely low levels for October and November, the survey will be
bad news for Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor. He has been hoping that his
package of growth measures in the November 1992 Autumn Statement, with
recent cuts in interest rates, will have lifted sentiment among consumers
and businesses as a prelude to economic recovery.
Consumer spending in the last quarter of last year fell 0.3 per cent
compared with the previous quarter after a 0.6 per cent quarter-on-quarter
fall in the July to September period, estimates from the survey suggest.
Mrs Bridget Rosewell, joint managing director of Business Strategies, said
the survey, based on interviews with 6,000 people, indicated that consumers
were 'shell shocked' by economic events. She said, however, that confidence
could gradually recover as the effects of the 3 percentage point fall in
base rates to 10 per cent since September start to bring down the cost of
mortgages.
The survey said Scotland, the Yorkshire and Humberside region and north-west
England saw the biggest falls in confidence in the fourth quarter compared
with the third. Previously people in these regions had been relatively
cheerful about the economic outlook.
