<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 93 / Lamont says civil servants suggested costs payment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NORMAN LAMONT, the chancellor, yesterday defended strongly his decision
to accept a Treasury contribution towards his personal legal costs as
backbench MPs prepared to call this week for tighter rules on all payments
to ministers.
Mr Lamont said he had not solicited the Pounds 4,700 paid by the Treasury
towards legal costs arising from the eviction of a self-styled sex therapist
from his London home.
He insisted on BBC television that the payment had been suggested by senior
civil servants after they judged that the proportion of his legal expenses
covering press relations was attributable to his public office.
The remainder of the bill for solicitors Peter Carter-Ruck and Partners was
met by an anonymous Pounds 18,000 donation channelled through Conservative
Central Office.
His comments, confirmed last week in a report by National Audit Office, the
independent watchdog on government spending, are unlikely to deflect Labour
attacks on the payment.
Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, has signalled a concerted attack on what
he regards as a general decline of standards in public office.
Later this week the opposition will highlight the business links of former
cabinet ministers with privatised industries, arguing that their influence
is behind the government's refusal to tackle 'excess' profits.
The cross-party Commons committee on members' interests will today add fuel
to the controversy over Mr Lamont's legal bill by arguing that anonymous
donations should in future be declared in the register of member's
interests.
The report attaches no direct blame to Mr Lamont for failing to do so,
concluding that the existing rules are not clear on the point.
Labour MPs are preparing to press the chancellor on whether he declared the
gift for income tax purposes. Yesterday Mr Lamont indicated he regarded his
tax affairs as a personal matter.
Separately, MPs on the Commons public accounts committee will this week
question former and present Treasury officials on the Pounds 4,700
contribution.
A majority on the committee is expected to back tighter accounting rules
which would alert parliament to all such payments.
</TEXT>
