<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 93 / SFO chief sees bigger role for City tribunals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FINANCIAL CRIMES are likely to be prosecuted more often by City tribunals
rather than through the criminal courts, according to the Serious Fraud
Office, which is responsible for investigating and prosecuting complex and
serious fraud.
The City's self-regulatory organisations each have tribunals with the power
to prosecute firms and individuals for breaches of their rules.
Mr George Staple, the SFO's director, said: 'In the past we have not given
sufficient weight to the City's separate regulatory regime.'
He refused to comment on specific cases, but there has been widespread
criticism of the SFO's decisions to prosecute all defendants in the Blue
Arrow and Guinness cases through the criminal courts.
Some lawyers believe aspects of those cases might have been more effectively
prosecuted through City tribunals.
The Securities and Futures Authority, the regulator of the securities
industry, has a tribunal with powers to disqualify firms and individuals
from practising in the City and to levy unlimited fines, although there is a
Pounds 50,000 limit on the amount it can force a defendant to pay in
restitution to anyone suffering as a result of a breach.
An executive with the authority said its tribunal had been used 'seven or
eight times' in the past couple of years, but not in any of the recent
high-profile fraud cases.
A City tribunal could only have been used in the Guinness and Blue Arrow
cases - or in any case of serious financial malpractice - with the SFO's
permission. According to Mr Staple a tribunal cannot operate if the SFO
decides to mount a criminal prosecution, because it might prejudice the
criminal hearing.
The advantage of a tribunal, Mr Staple said, was that the judge was an
expert and the level of proof required for a successful prosecution was less
than in a criminal court. He wanted a tribunal to have 'full powers' to
award compensation to a victim.
He stressed that courts would be used for cases of serious fraud involving
City firms or individuals.
The powers of City tribunals to prosecute and punish are being examined by
Mr Andrew Large, chairman of the Securities and Investments Board, as part
of the government-sponsored review of UK financial regulation.
Mr Staple said there was an argument for giving SIB civil powers to
prosecute alleged insider dealers. He was opposed to decriminalising the
offence, even though there had been calls from City practitioners for this
and widespread criticisms of the government's proposed new insider-dealing
legislation.
Reformed City tribunals might play a role if plea bargaining is introduced
as an option in fraud cases, as Mr Staple has recommended.
Mr Staple said that in an appropriate case a plea of guilty from an
individual in a criminal case could bring him or her a lesser prison
sentence than might otherwise be expected, or a conditional discharge.
The conditions of the discharge might include payment of a substantial fine,
full co-operation with any continuing investigation, regulatory penalties
imposed by an SRO such as ceasing to do business in a market, or restitution
to the victim.
Mr Staple also called for a simplification of the financial regulatory
system. 'If the law (including its institutions) is unclear, people will
find ways round it'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
