<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 93 / Squabble over jobs sours transition: Republican resignations
could lead to early chaos in the new administration
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ONE of the recurring sounds of the last two months has been that of
President-elect Bill Clinton saying how fully he supports outgoing President
George Bush in his handling of foreign policy challenges such as Somalia and
Iraq.
At home, however, there has been more friction between the departing
Republicans and the arriving Democrats; in the days before Mr Bush hands
over to his successor on Wednesday, relations between the two transition
teams have turned sour over the question of jobs.
A new president in the US always brings a turnover in federal staff that is
unmatched in other western democracies, but the Clinton team has irritated
the Bush officials handling the transition by asking for an unusually
sweeping and immediate set of resig-nations.
The White House has taken the Clinton request literally, and will put the
resignations of about 650 top officials, whose replacements are subject to
Senate confirmation, into effect at noon on Wednesday.
This creates the potential for chaos, as Mr Clinton has fallen behind
schedule in picking people to fill second- and third-tier jobs in his
administration, and will have no one ready to pick up the reins of
government.
Mr Kevin Moley, deputy secretary of health and human services, told the New
York Times that the resignations would make clear the Clinton team's lack of
expertise. 'That's what the American people voted for on November 3. Now the
consequences will come home to roost,' he said.
At the same time, however, the Bush administration has decided to give Mr
Clinton no help in rooting out lower-level political appointees, whose
resignations have also been asked for.
Despite Mr Clinton's early talk of including Republicans in his
administration, it is clear there are too many Democrats looking for
government jobs to keep more than a tiny handful of Bush appointees in
office.
</TEXT>
