<DATE>930118
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 93 / Attack widens target range: Cheney argues for keeping up
sanctions, denying Saddam the ability to rebuild his forces
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM and PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT George Bush's decision yesterday to launch a missile strike
against an Iraqi nuclear facility moves the allied response to President
Saddam Hussein's challenges a notch higher.
Mr Marlin Fitzwater, White House spokesman, warned yesterday that US concern
about Iraq's intentions was growing. The Tomahawk missile launch made clear
the riposte had also moved a notch higher.
Over the last few weeks Mr Saddam has challenged the UN, particularly the
US, Britain and France, on different fronts: bomb attacks on UN relief
lorries in Kurdistan, threatening missile and aircraft movements in the two
no-fly zones, raids across the Kuwaiti border, and obstructions to movement
of UN inspectors charged with destroying Iraq's nuclear, chemical and
biological weapons capability.
Until yesterday, only the challenges in the no-fly zones had drawn a
military response. Allied fighters shot down an Iraqi Mig aircraft violating
the southern zone late last month; on Wednesday, they bombed missile and
radar sites in the zone. Yesterday they shot down another Mig in the
northern zone, and fired a missile at radar locked on to allied aircraft.
Yesterday's Tomahawk attack extends the range of targets beyond the no-fly
zones.
Pentagon doctrine has generally held that if you are to use military force
against an opponent, you should use it overwhelmingly. Last Wednesday's air
raid has strengthened the hand of those who question the effectiveness of
such limited attacks.
For several days some officers have argued for an assault over several days,
targeting troops, air defence sites and nuclear plants. The coalition seems
anxious to keep some proportion between Mr Saddam's challenges to UN
resolutions and the punishment. By attacking a nuclear factory, the
coalition kept a direct link to the obstruction of UN inspection flights.
Mr Richard Cheney, US defence secretary, suggested the coalition had little
prospect of shaping Mr Saddam's behaviour by its military actions, but
argued that the important aim was to maintain sanctions against the Iraqi
leader, preventing him rebuilding his military forces.
Philip Stephens, Political Editor, adds: The UK government last night
offered unequivocal backing for the latest air strike against Iraq,
insisting the action was fully underpinned by UN resolutions. But amid
growing concern that Mr Saddam is determined to step up his confrontation
with the west, it was privately acknowledged in Whitehall that the coalition
against him faces important constraints.
Downing Street stressed that the facility attacked was one of those on the
inspection list of the UN Special Commission.
The missiles were fired only after personal consultations between Mr Bush
and other western leaders, and with the UN weapons inspectorate team.
Diplomatic contacts had been concerted with Arab governments to reassure
them of the coalition's intentions. Officials conceded that military
advisers would have preferred a severer assault, directed at Iraq's military
capacity, especially its air defences.
But the Bush administration's anxiety not to risk US aircrews and the
concern of its partners, including Britain, not to fall outside the UN
resolutions, argued for a limited strike.
Officials denied a split with Washington over the timing and scale of the
latest operation. But Mr Major is keen to keep the unity which has given him
all-party backing at Westminster for military enforcement of UN resolutions.
A dozen or so Labour MPs oppose military action, but the proportionate
nature of the strikes so far has ensured Mr Major the support of both the
Labour and Liberal Democrat leaders.
</TEXT>
