<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 93 / Danish centrists offer hope for SDP leader
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HILARY BARNES and Agencies
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   COPENHAGEN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Poul Nyrup Rasmussen, the leader of Denmark's opposition Social
Democratic party, moved closer yesterday to becoming prime minister of
Denmark when a pivotal centrist party said it would probably back him.
The small Radical Liberal party, holding the balance of power in parliament,
said after an all-day meeting it would support him if inter-party talks on a
government programme were successful.
'We are now concentrating on creating the best possible government programme
and if this is successful it would be natural that Rasmussen becomes prime
minister,' Radical Liberal leader Marianne Jelved said after the party
meeting in the town of Nyborg.
Mr Rasmussen will resume talks today, seeking either a minority SDP
government or a coalition of the SDP and the Radical Liberals.
Mr Schluter, prime minister since 1982, resigned last Thursday when a
judicial inquiry found that he had misled the Folketing (parliament) in 1989
over the so-called 'Tamilgate' scandal, in which Mr Erik Ninn-Hansen, the
former minister of justice, illegally ordered civil servants to delay
issuing entry visas to the wives and children of Tamil refugees from Sri
Lanka.
There appears to be majority support among the parties in the Folketing for
impeachment proceedings against Mr Ninn-Hansen. If such proceedings are
instituted it will be for the first time since 1910.
An impeachment trial is conducted by the 15 judges of the High Court, who
sit together with 15 persons appointed by the Folketing, none of whom may be
MPs.
Tamilgate has not led to an increase in the popularity of the SDP, according
to opinion polls. A poll published in Jyllands Posten yesterday showed the
SDP sliding by four points to 33.4 per cent from 37.4 per cent in the 1990
election. The chief beneficiary of the scandal, which has seriously damaged
the Conservative party, is the Liberal party of Mr Uffe Ellemann-Jensen,
foreign minister, which went ahead to 23.9 per cent compared with 15.8 per
cent in the last election.
The possibility of an SDP government has been accepted with equanimity by
the financial markets.
One reason is that the party's economic policy spokesman, Mr Mogens
Lykkteft, has said that an SDP government would continue to pursue tight
public spending policies and would maintain the fixed exchange rate policy
through continued participation in the European exchange rate mechanism.
Among the tasks for a new prime minister is running the rotating European
Community presidency, in Copenhagen's hands since January 1.
Denmark also faces a crucial second referendum in late April or May on the
landmark Maastricht treaty on European economic and political union, after
Danes said No in a first vote last June.
Mr Rasmussen is a staunch supporter of a revised Maastricht deal exempting
Danes from the treaty's long-term aims for a common currency and joint
defence policies.
Danish news media predicted that if the government programme was accepted by
a majority Mr Rasmussen could replace Mr Schluter by the middle of this
week.
</TEXT>
