<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 93 / Chancellor damps hopes of interest rate cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN and PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NORMAN Lamont, the chan-cellor, yesterday signalled a cautious approach
to further UK interest rate cuts by stressing that the government faced a
difficult task keeping inflation in its target range.
Appearing on BBC Television's 'Breakfast with Frost' programme, the
chancellor said there were 'many encouraging signs' that the economy was
improving. He also insisted there was 'very little room for manoeuvre' if
the government was to keep to its target of holding underlying inflation
between 1 and 4 per cent over the life of this parliament.
These remarks in a wide-ranging but soft-centred interview with Sir David
Frost suggested the chancellor was in no hurry to approve a further cut in
bank base rates from 7 per cent. This follows speculation in financial
markets last week that interest rate cuts were imminent.
His comments came as officials confirmed that Mr John Major has set up a
cabinet committee to suggest new schemes to tackle rising unemployment. With
the jobless total set to rise above 3m over the next few months, the prime
minister is anxious to show that the government is minimising unemployment's
damaging impact on confidence.
The Treasury has so far resisted calls from other Whitehall departments for
a large-scale jobs programme in the Budget on March 16.
A report from Full Employment UK, a policy consultancy, to be presented to
the prime minister this week, estimates it would cost over Pounds 630m to
operate an obligatory scheme to take 400,000 long-term unemployed off the
dole queue.
Mr Lamont reaffirmed that the government aimed to bring underlying
inflation, which excludes mortgage interest payments, to between zero and 2
per cent by the end of this parliament. He made clear that this would not be
easy.
Official figures issued last Friday showed the underlying inflation rate
crept up to 3.7 per cent last month from 3.6 per cent in November. Speaking
of the 1 to 4 per cent target range, the chancellor said: 'It sounds a
rather generous target, but it isn't. It is very tough by the standards of
the past.'
Mr Lamont said the impact on inflation of sterling's depreciation since
leaving the European exchange rate mechanism had been less than feared. But
it was 'early days yet' and the lower than expected boost to prices was
probably because the disinflationary forces in the economy had been so
strong before the September 16 currency crisis.
The chancellor denied that the pound's departure from the ERM had left the
government's anti-inflation strategy in tatters. He admitted, though, that
the sterling crisis had acted as a 'shattering blow to confidence'.
He stressed that the floating of sterling had also created opportunities;
the government had been able to cut interest rates while conditions had
improved for exporters. But he said currency depreciation could 'never' be
the answer to Britain's economic problems. 'It is in the long term the road
to ruin,' he said. The right way to improve performance was to become
competitive.
A welter of economic data this week should give a clearer idea of how far
Britain's economy has recovered since departure from the ERM and the
adoption in November of policies to encourage growth. The British Chambers
of Commerce quarterly business survey, on Thursday, is expected to confirm
the picture of greater optimism conveyed by smaller business surveys and
reports of high turnover in the winter sales.
Mr Lamont agreed with Sir David that growth in Britain 'could be better'
this year than the 1 per cent forecast in the Autumn Statement. Although he
insisted he was sticking to his forecast of 'around 1 per cent growth', Mr
Lamont said he expected activity would accelerate to a higher growth rate in
the second half of this year and to a faster rate next year.
'Obviously, one has to be cautious before ringing the bell and saying the
recession is over,' he said. But there were 'good trends' in retail sales,
car sales and production.
Confidence 'at ebb', Page 6
Lamont defends payment, Page 6
Observer, Page 11
