<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JAN 93 / International Company News: Westinghouse Electric and GE
Capital talks fail
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WESTINGHOUSE Electric and GE Capital have terminated talks which might have
led to GE Capital buying some or all of the loan portfolio of Westinghouse's
troubled financial services unit.
Westinghouse's shares fell on the news to close at Dollars 13 3/4 , down
Dollars 1, last night. Wall Street had regarded a sale to GE as a quick and
tidy way for Westinghouse to shed the problem.
GE declined to comment further but Westinghouse said in a statement that its
finan-cial adviser, Morgan Stanley, believed that 'substantially more value
should be realised by a programme of individual and small pool sales than
the sale to GE Capital would have created'.
Westinghouse, which has been plagued by property loan problems for two
years, decided last November to get out of financial services, though it
said then it could take three years to sell off its assets.
Westinghouse said yesterday it was confident that it would achieve the
liquidations and values contained in November's plan and added that numerous
parties had expressed an interest in the financial services business.
This is the second time talks between the two companies have come to
nothing. In December 1991, GE cast an eye over the credit unit's assets, but
it was apparently interested in buying only a few of them.
</TEXT>
