<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JAN 93 / UK Company News: Prudential new UK business up 13% - Shares
advance as market welcomes better-than-expected figures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRUDENTIAL Corporation, the life assurance group, reported a 13.3 per cent
increase in UK new business last year. New business outside the UK, partly
boosted by currency movements was up by 11.7 per cent, although most of this
was accounted for by the sterling's devaluation.
The market welcomed the figures, which were better than expected, and the
shares closed at 296p, up 9p on the day.
Single premium products performed far more strongly than regular premiums,
which were damaged by low consumer confidence. Total UK single premium
business increased from Pounds 1.41bn to Pounds 1.97bn, while annual
premiums failed to keep up with inflation, rising from Pounds 320m to Pounds
325m.
Mr Peter Nowell, group chief actuary, attributed the single premium rise to
increased pension transfer business, caused by people moving jobs or taking
early retirement.
Annual life premiums fell from Pounds 136m to Pounds 126m, but life single
premiums more than doubled to Pounds 846m. This was almost entirely due to
sales of the Prudence Bond, the Prudential's single-premium with-profits
bond, which took in Pounds 835m.
Mr Roman Cizdyn, an analyst at Smith New Court, said that both pension
transfers and the Prudence Bond should be more profitable than most single
premium products, as it was difficult for customers to surrender the
policies. The company's right to make a market value adjustment on pay-outs
from the Prudence Bond meant that it should not impose a great capital
strain, he said. Scottish Mutual, the life assurance company wholly owned by
Abbey National saw total new business of Pounds 179.4m for 1992, up 29 per
cent from 1991's Pounds 139.4m.
Total single premiums rose 41 per cent to Pounds 158.1m, while regular
premiums fell 21 per cent to Pounds 21.2m. This was a sharper drop than that
experienced by the few companies which have so far reported, but Mr Cizdyn
said he believed it would prove to be in line with the industry trend.
United Friendly, the life assurance group, announced an increase in annual
premium business from Pounds 20.6m to Pounds 25.9m. This change, starkly
against the industry trend, was attributed to sharply increased agency
sales.
The company may also have benefited from switches from other companies,
following the decision of some rivals to raise their minimum premiums.
Single premium business, again helped by pension transfers, more than
doubled from Pounds 20.4m to Pounds 41.9m.
The shares rose 9p to close at 513p.
</TEXT>
