FT  15 JAN 93 / EC non-committal on coal aid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICHAEL HESELTINE, trade and industry secretary, received a non-committal
response yesterday from the European Commission to his outline proposals for
supporting the UK coal industry.
Mr Heseltine met Mr Karel Van Miert, the new competition commissioner, and
Mr Abel Matutes, who has taken over responsibility for energy and transport,
for general discussions about EC and UK policy.
As expected, neither commissioner was able to comment in detail on the UK
suggestions, which have not yet been adopted by the British cabinet. Mr
Heseltine wants to ease the pressure on the British industry, and has
considered the imposition of a system of levies on consumers' electricity
bills. That would amount to an indirect subsidy that would allow generators
to buy British coal.
An official for Mr Matutes said that the commissioner would study Mr
Heseltine's plans, but it was too early to say what reaction the commission
might have. British diplomats said Mr Heseltine had not come to Brussels
expecting a firm response from the new commissioners.
</TEXT>
