<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Growth stock focus gives Dow
support
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
BLUE CHIPS once again lagged behind the broader market as demand for
technology and small-capitalisation growth stocks helped to offset earnings
disappointments elsewhere, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 4.32 at 3,267.88. The
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 put on 2.91 at 435.94 and the Nasdaq composite jumped
8.92 to set another record close of 695.70. Trading volume on the New York
SE came to 304.5m shares.
News of a 52,000 rise in weekly jobless claims surprised the market, because
the drop reversed the recent trend for improving job market conditions. This
was offset by better news on retail sales, which rose 1.2 per cent in
December. There was also good news on inflation, with the Labor Department
announcing that producer prices were up just 0.2 per cent last month.
With many investors still apprehensive about the immediate outlook for stock
prices and willing to wait until the quarterly reporting season is over,
leading issues remained locked in a narrow range.
Leading indices were pulled in different directions by a big loss in JP
Morgan on disappointing figures and a solid rise in some big technology
issues which reported stronger than expected earnings.
JP Morgan dropped Dollars 3 1/8 to Dollars 61 1/2 in volume of 2.3m shares
after reporting that profits rose 11 per cent in the fourth quarter to
Dollars 298m, or Dollars 1.48 a share. Although the net income figure was
slightly higher than forecasts, analysts were disappointed with JP Morgan's
operating earnings.
Motorola jumped Dollars 10 7/8 to Dollars 123 1/4 as investors reacted
positively to the news that fourth quarter profits reached Dollars 181m, up
from Dollars 126m a year earlier.
Digital Equipment was also in favour, soaring Dollars 7 3/8 to Dollars 42
1/4 in volume of 5.5m shares on news that the computer group's fiscal second
quarter losses narrowed to Dollars 73.8m, down from a figure of Dollars
155.2m a year ago.
The good news from the sector lifted other technology stocks, with IBM
rising Dollars 1 to Dollars 48 3/4 , Compaq putting on Dollars 3 1/8 at
Dollars 53 3/4 and Hewlett-Packard adding Dollars 2 7/8 at Dollars 74 1/8 .
Coca-Cola rose Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 43 1/4 on reports that international
unit case volume in December was 11 per cent higher than the year before, a
big improvement on previous estimates of overseas sales growth.
Canada
TORONTO stocks ended generally higher after an active session filled with
corporate news. A trader said that we seem to have turned around at the end
of the day, following New York higher, but golds and financials are still
pretty soft.
The TSE 300 index improved 5.5 to 3,303.8 and rises exceeded falls by 321 to
288. Volume amounted to 44.7m shares.
Molson A shares rose CDollars 1 to CDollars 29 1/4 on news that Philip
Morris's unit, Miller Brewing Co, will buy 20 per cent of Molson Breweries
for USDollars 273m.
